---
description: "New Feature Development Guidelines"
globs:
alwaysApply: true
---

- **Plan Before Coding:** Before implementing a new feature, break down the feature requirements and design a solution that fits into the existing system. Identify which modules or components need changes or additions. Consider edge cases and how the feature will scale or interact with other parts of the system. It can be useful to outline this plan in comments or a design document for complex features.  
- **Follow Project Structure:** Implement the feature within the project’s established structure. For example, if adding a new vision analysis function, place it in the appropriate module (rather than creating a duplicate structure). Reuse existing utilities or services whenever possible instead of reinventing them. This keeps the codebase DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself) and consistent.  
- **Incremental Implementation:** Develop the feature in manageable increments. Write the core functionality first, then integrate it step by step. After each significant change, run the application or tests to ensure nothing is broken. For instance, if adding a new API endpoint, first create the endpoint function, then connect it to the router, then test it in isolation, and finally update the UI (if applicable) to call this API.  
- **Testing During Development:** As you implement new features, write corresponding tests (unit tests or integration tests) to verify the new behavior. Ensure existing tests continue to pass; this guards against regressions. If the project doesn’t have a formal test suite, manually test the new feature’s behavior in various scenarios. For example, if the feature is an image upload, test with different image sizes and formats to ensure robustness.  
- **Documentation and Examples:** Once the feature is complete, update documentation (per the Documentation rule) and provide examples or tutorials if appropriate. For a user-facing feature, make sure usage instructions are clear. For an internal API or library feature, consider adding an example usage in the README or a dedicated examples section. This helps others (and future you) understand how to utilize the new functionality.  
- **Code Review Mindset:** Write the code as if it will be reviewed by a senior engineer or an open-source community. This means clear code, thorough error checking, and consistency with style. Before considering the feature "done," do a self-review or ask Cursor to perform a *code review* to catch any issues or improvements. Address any identified problems (edge cases, potential bugs, performance issues) before finalizing the feature implementation.  
